  "style": "",
  "texts": [
    "For our analysis, we randomly select 10,000 Congressional bills and separately prompt GPT-3.5-Turbo and GPT-4o to label each Congressional bill for its policy area using alternative prompting strategies, including base prompts that modify the requested format, persona modifications, chainof-thought modifications, and even few-shot examples (see Appendix E.4 for the specific prompts we used).",
    "Consequently, for each Congressional bill description r, we obtain labels V m,p r associated with two different large language models m and twelve prompting strategies p. Appendix Figure A4 calculates the pairwise agreement in the labels produced by alternative prompting strategies p. We again find substantial variation in the pairwise agreement in the labels produced, and there appear to be no consistent patterns in which pairs of prompting strategies tend to have the most agreement.",
    "We then separately regress the labeled economic concept -in this case, the policy topic of the bill -against linked covariates W r, separately reporting the coefficients β m,p and their associated t-statistics.",
    "Figure 5 summarizes the variation in the resulting t-statistics across models and prompts: each column shows the result of using LLM labels V m,p r for alternative bill topics as the dependent variable (i.e., Health, Banking, Finance and Domestic Commerce, Defense, Government Operations, and Public Lands and Water Management), and each row shows the result using a different linked covariate W r (i.e., whether the bill's sponsor was a Democrat, whether the bill originated in the Senate, and the DW1 score of the bill's sponsor).",
    "Table 3 summarizes the coefficient estimates across models and prompts for each choice of labeled policy topic and the covariate."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}